segments.text: Let's see.
When did you hear that Jack Williams was the new president?
How did you hear?
I heard in 1971.
Do you remember a moment or a conversation?
Mr. Heaton told me.
I think that at that time they had the...
The executive committee preceded the APC.
The executive committee at that time was made up of the president of the university and all the deans and the vice presidents.
Although Mr. Heaton was not a, well he would have been a dean at that time.
Mr. Heaton was always on all of the major committees at the university, even when he was a director.
And I believe that he had, there had been a, there had been a call meeting, was, General Ludeke was acting president, if I'm not mistaken, at that time.
And I believe there had been a call meeting, and I assume that he got his information from the executive committee and told us that Dr. Williams would be named president of the university.
Do you remember your
first encounter or first meeting?
Well, I knew who Dr. Williams was because of his assignment at the Coordinating Board.
I believe he was the first commissioner of the Coordinating Board.

See, I did a lot of work with the Coordinating Board in doing all the reports for the university, the student academic reports and things like that, although I didn't work with Dr. Williams, but I knew a lot of the staff over there and I knew who he was.
And so I was...
So I was acquainted with him.
I didn't know anything about his style or anything like that at all.
As you arrived, as he arrived I mean, do you remember any major changes or anything?
How did he enter A&M?
What was his style?
It seems to me that there were a lot of changes made in the committee structures that I recall that took place fairly quickly after he came in and out.
Certainly he had his blessings.
I don't know if he was the architect, so to speak, of it, but that was the time that the ABC came into being, I believe.
Is that correct?
Yeah, I think so.
I think that's when, and I know Dr. Calhoun and Dr. Minerty had a lot of input on that.
Dr. Williams, I felt, didn't, it didn't seem to me, it maybe was because of the relationship that Mr.
Rudder had with a lot of us who'd been here a long time,
It seemed to me that it took us a while to get to know Dr. Williams.
After we got to know him, we felt more comfortable.
And it may have been because of the assignment that he had and what he was trying to do.
The university, Dr. General Ludeke, of course, was acting president at that time, but it could be that
A lot of things were being helped on the burner, so to speak, until they got in a full-time president.
And when he got here, he might have had his plates loaded, and he was not as accessible as maybe we thought he should be.
But that later changed.
And then I got to know him fairly well because of our graduation ceremonies and being on the stage with him and that sort of thing.
Describe his manner at graduation.
Oh, very elated with the function.
He loved it.
He was very cordial to the students.
You could tell that he felt it was a wonderful ceremony.
And I think, of course, anybody that comes to A&M Commencement, most schools that they've been to, don't have what this institution offers here.
And most presidents or deans that are at other schools and come down here and see what we do are extremely impressed with it.
And I think he loved every moment of it.
I never heard him say that he disliked any aspect of it.
There were certain things that he would have done his particular way and that sort of thing.
And that's understandable.
And we did it.
As I said earlier, I think we're where we are today because of his administration.
Now, he selects Calhoun as his chief academic officer not long after he got here.
Describe Calhoun, the administrator, from your point of view as the registrar.
Well, I thought at first,
that Dr. Calhoun might look on us as a necessary evil kind, so to speak.
And that probably had a lot to do with all the programs that he had interest in and that sort of thing.
Gee, I always thought our salvation in that operation down there was Haskell and Rowe.

Because, as you know, we became more or less responsible, directly responsible for you, and I think you always understood our... You have to understand when you ask a question like that, I have to look and see what kind of attention were we getting.
Dr. Calhoun, as I say, he... And I understand that from his background, from his education.
I mean, you know, research, teaching...

all the the curriculum the academic programs and things like that was certainly most important to him he knew that we had to have the function of what we did over there so it was wise on his part i think to have someone like you that understood what what we were all about and gave us the support so but
Dr. Calhoun did a wonderful job.
I mean, he did a superior job in leading the school and that sort of thing.
You know, when you get close to administrators and whatnot, you can't help but compare.
And so that's, you know, I'm not trying to say anything negative about him because he and I got along.
And Dr. Rinerdi and I got along.
But it just, you feel like when someone is aware and is tuned in to what you're doing, then you have to make a comparison between former administrators.
And not that it's negative, it wasn't negative for any of them.
I think John did a good job.
One of the practices I think I remember throughout all these years was a,
session between every graduating senior in the last semester and a representative of the registrar looking at their transcript to be sure that, where did that begin?
Do you know?
Before I answer that, let me say one thing about John Calhoun.
Oh, okay.
Please do.
John Calhoun implemented the Texas A&M that was the finest, greatest,
working committee that that campus had ever seen, and that was called the Academic Operations Committee.
He put that in.
The Academic Operations Committee, if you remember, was made up of all of the assistant or associate deans and the registrar or admissions people.
And it brought us together like nothing before had ever done.
And we could sit there and talk about our problems and our plans
And it just made our work, everybody knew what the other person was doing, what to expect, what we were going to do, and that sort of thing.
I always felt that that was just a tremendous decision.
I don't know if he was under his administration.
I don't know if it was his idea or whose idea it was that he got done.
It's still there.
It's still working.
And people today tell me that it's
still one of the best committees out there.
I always thought it was the people at the real working level where you could throw theory out the door.
Here it was down at the grassroots.
And they worked with students, and that's what this was all about.
Every one of them had students.
We had the students to deal with and their records.
And a prime example of that was when we then took
a large number of those people that were on that committee when I implemented this touchstone registration system and this total automated record system that we finally got in.
I had those people on my committee.
It's a working committee.
John Calhoun, I give him credit for that.
I'm sorry.
I was going to digress a second.
The conference that
You're absolutely correct.
Every student that was a candidate for a degree, you came in and you filed for a degree, you filed a degree application form in your last semester to graduate.
And a record was checked.

and uh if you had and then each student was sent a letter and in that letter it said you're clear or you have problems so if you had problems you had to excuse me uh in the earlier days uh whether you had problems didn't have problems you had to go in and have that conference you had to go in and sit down and talk to an assistant registrar that was in charge of graduation and it was just a counseling session where the

office went over your your record and you were clear that was it you were out if you had difficulties such as substitutions and all that kind of stuff then you were directed to go over to the dean's office and get these substitutions approved and that sort of thing short on grade points it was a final check the problem i always had with that it was a little bit late

you know why should a student be given a paper or a letter uh two months before he was graduating and if he couldn't go register for a course which he couldn't that late then what does he do he's here for another semester so that was another thing that we worked on to try to get that out early in the student's career and with these academic advisors i talked to you about a while ago and after we got all this automation see every semester when those grades are applied
By terminal now, that academic faculty or that faculty member can sit there, call up John Doe's record, see right where it is, tell him what the deficiencies are, what his extra hours are, whatever.
So changes can be made way prior to the last semester.
And surely there must be some good anecdotes from those conversations with those students who thought they were going to graduate.
Well, not having done any of that myself, that was one thing that I never did do up there, although we had people doing it.
I'm kind of lost at that, Haskell.
All right, was it your direct responsibility then to see to it that
All the correct diplomas were here for the people.
That's correct.
As you know, for many, many, many, many years, up until, well, they were doing it in 1998.
When I did my last commencement, they were doing it in May of 88.
It's not done today.
Oh, really?
Uh-huh.
The diplomas are up there.
Uh-huh.
But there are students that are walking across the stage who may or may not have fallen by for graduation.
Prior to 1988, nobody crossed that stage unless they were certified and all the hot wax or whatever were put on their diploma and got the real diploma.
Describe the routine you all went through to get all those diplomas in the right order
So they could be handed out.
Okay.
Well, again, the student applied for a degree in the semester in which they were to finish.
And so we had a list going.
And this was done by colleges and done by, broken down by department and by degree.
And the diplomas were ordered.
You also had to file, pay a diploma fee and order your diploma.
All the diplomas were ordered.
There was a cutoff date.
For example, in the fall semester, the cutoff date would be around the 15th of October.
You had from September the 1st or now August the 30th or whatever up to September, October the 15th to order your diploma.
Everybody's diplomas were ordered who applied for them.
And the diploma company would print them and get them into us.
So we had them all there prior to, you know, a month or so before graduation.
And we'd go ahead, and at the same time, we were building a program, a commencement program.
And there would always be a lot of students that knew they weren't going to graduate, so they'd come in and tell you, hey, I'm not going to make it.
Their name would be taken off the list.
So we had a program built as early as November the 1st.
And we just kept that as our master list.
And then on that magic cutoff day, which was Thursday at 5 o'clock prior to the ceremony on Friday, well, that would be it.
And we posted a master list in the office, and all the people who were still candidates,
come in and they blew.
They had a red dot by their name.
They were clear.
If it didn't have a red dot by their name, then they had a problem.
And they had to file a clock on Thursday and cleared it up.
And after that, then, we went down to the A&M Printing Center that night, and by about midnight, we had our commencement program finished.
While we were down there having the programs completed, Don Carter and his group
would be over in the office with a duplicate list of the commencement program, stacking the diplomas in the order in which they would be given out.
And they were going to put on those large racks that you've seen there on the stage.
And on the outside of each tube was a name.
That's right.
And as you know, we have a caller.
And of course, those diplomas are stacked in reverse order, such that you come out at the top and you're correct.
And since we graduate by colleges, then they all have to be done, then they're alphabetical within degree.

All the bachelor of science degrees will be, I mean all the master of science degrees will be here, but if you're getting a bachelor of science in economics, then they're alphabetical within economics, and then following that might be physics, and then they're alphabetical within that.
The key to the man standing at the diploma rack is the collar.
He's got to be sure that when he calls that name, the diploma there matches.
It's quite an ordeal to get that done properly.
Did any of them ever get spilled on stage?
No, I don't think we ever had an accident like that.
We have had a time or two where there would not be a diploma for a person.
And we kept a box down by the side of the rack
It had nothing but the empty white tube.
And, of course, we'd just pick it up, hand it to the president, and the audience never knew what happened.
Now, the recipient knew what happened, and they were kind of hot when they got out in the audience and opened up and found that they had nothing inside.
I mean, they usually were back up at the stage asking questions after the ceremony.
More often than not, what was the situation for those that got a blank?
Oh, well, it could be two or three things.
One, it could be that the student didn't qualify.
He or she, we look on the master list, and they didn't have a red dot, and they were short grade points, or they hadn't completed this particular course or whatever.
It could be that we might have made a mistake.
As much as you check those things and check those things, sometimes they'll get by.
And for whatever those reasons were, there just wasn't one there.
I think those were the two categories.
Do you remember any situations where the wrong tube went to the wrong person?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Yes, I can recall doing that.
And that simply came because you might make a mistake yourself.
You'd look down, and you'd hear a name, and you might just pick the wrong tube.
You want to pick the one next to it up.
And in my case, the years that I did that, as soon as I handed it to the president, I knew it was wrong.
But instead of taking it back from him, the next guy would get a blank tube, and we'd be back on track then after that.
Now, normally you and Don Carter, in the years that I was familiar, you all worked that.
He pulled it out and handed it to you?
That's correct.
That's correct.
And then I did that until I became executive director.
And then after that, Don did it all with the business.
Yes, I did that from Mr. Perriman was doing it for a while.
And then I guess I started doing that in 1969.
And I did it until 86.
When you graduated, was it?
Did you get your diploma in a tube?
Exactly the same, sir.
The president was there, handed the diploma to me, and it was a real joy.
As far as I know, we've done that.
I don't know when, which would be an interesting question to find an answer to.
How long have they been doing that?
Or did they do that?
Because I agree with you, there are not many institutions today that still truly hand out diplomas.
There are not many institutions where almost every student attends.
We have a high percentage of attendance.
And therefore, there is given to that student and his or her family a very warm feeling about the last event.
Do you remember any last-minute crises relating to commencements?
Well, we'd have the usual one.
You can imagine the disappointment.

I don't think I'm talking to you, maybe not answering your question, but the big disappointment would be because former students of Texas A&M University don't think that the university ever makes mistakes or that they should make mistakes.
I mean, I've had them call me on the phone and say, you guys don't make mistakes.
We don't make, Aggies don't make mistakes.
Of course, it would be a great letdown when a kid, we wouldn't have a diploma for him or he'd open his empty tooth.
And you'd have families that would come up, but they would always be, after they understood what the situation was, hey, we're going to take care of you.
Many times on Saturday morning, we'd take them back over to the office and we found what the problem was and everything was solved at that time.
But you never had a crisis where the diplomas didn't get here on time, where the program didn't get printed?
The crisis I remember, no, to answer your question, no, about the diplomas.
I don't recall that in my area at all.
The big crisis that we were up against at one time had to do with the printing of the program.
We had been down there all night, as I told you.
Well, actually, we finished it at about midnight.
We got back to the office, and one of the people that was helping just happened to be thumbing through the program, and we were awarding a posthumous degree that year.
And as you recall, we always had an asterisk by the name, and then the footnote, posthumous, posthumously awarded, posthumously, I think is what it said.
The word posthumously was misspelled.
We have printed some 7, 8, 10,000 of these programs.
We did nothing.
We called back down to go back by daylight the next morning or by 8 or 9 o'clock the next morning.
We had a correct set, properly spelled posthumously.
So that kind of put us in a bind.
It was a pressure deal, obviously, all the time, because it was a pressure on the faculty.
Because the students were there, and they were particularly students who had difficulties.
They were there bugging them and trying to get the professor to make a grade change, or let me write an extra paper.
And they were working right up to this 5 o'clock.
One story that I'll never forget, and this involves your former department head of history,
Dr. Nance.
I will not mention the student's name because I don't think maybe I should.
The student here was a very prominent former student and a prominent person in the state, son of this man.
The interesting thing about this, I happened to be having lunch with Harry Green a week prior to the deadline for graduation.
And this young man came by, and Harry introduced him to me.
And he said, oh, I need to talk to you, Mr. Lacey.
I need to know just exactly what to do to make certain that my graduation is OK.
So I went through the rules with him.
5 o'clock comes on Thursday, and he hasn't cleared.
because he has an elf in a history course.
Well, we go on down to the printing center, and about 9 o'clock that night, I get a call from Dr. Williams.
Hold up.
We're going to do something.
And we've got to find Dr. Nance.
Well, you knowing Dr. Nance and his temperament, that kind of thing didn't sit well with him at all.
But anyway, about midnight,
They located Dr. Nance, and he was to retest this young man.
Well, the next problem was they couldn't find the young man.
So they finally found him about 3 o'clock in the morning up at the Dixie Chicken, and he was slightly on his way to a neighboration.
But the test was given, and I'm still holding up.
I'm still holding up on the printing.
So I go on from the printing center about 5 in the morning to the office.
It's 6 o'clock.
Somebody's knocking on the back doors of the Cokeville.
And I open the door, and here's Milton Nance in a roar, highly upset.
You know how red he'd get when he got angry.
And he went through his philosophy about all this stuff, and I don't think he'd repeat that.
But he had given an exam, and he
And we were able to- He had a grade change.
He had a grade change, and we were able to get his name in the program.
And Dr. Williams, I also remember that.
I mean, he said, look, I've done a lot of things, talking to this particular gentleman, I've done a lot of things, but this is the limit.
Don't ask me anymore.
I suspect you recall that circumstance.
Let's see, commencement speakers, do you have any favorites that you remember?
Oh, Len Ashby.
I thought you had no doubt about it.
Absolutely.
You know, we had him here at least twice, maybe three times.
Oh, I just remember I knew all about one.
I believe he's been here twice.
I believe he's been here twice, yes.
I remember him with Dr. Williams particularly.
Yes, yes.
You know, he was a University of Texas graduate.
He got a tremendous amount of respect for Texas A&M because of Jack Williams.
He really introduced him here, and he's been quite complimentary.
Do you remember any prima donnas who kind of acted uppity as commencement speakers?
Oh, Dr. DeBakey.
That would have been my choice too.
Not any question about it.
That he was doing us a favor by being here.
Totally, totally.
And acted as though he didn't enjoy him any more.
One I had great, I felt great honor in working with was Leon Jaworski.
You know, I remember when he was here, but when was that?
It was in the Williams years.
Late 70s?
No, it may have been under Jarvis.
I don't remember him as a speaker.
I just remember him as a kind, thoughtful man who would not accept the fee.
And I told him that we would then take his fee and make a scholarship out of it.
And he then wrote a check equaling that fee to add to it.
And I thought all the things that I've read about him, I... Let's see, do you remember...
On the stage, do you remember any student doing anything, any prank or anything goofy on the stage?
Oh, yes.
The one that comes to mind immediately is the student that comes up to the, if you recall, that was an elevated stage and we had rather inclined steps going up to it.
And so the student comes up to the bottom of the steps
And he's on crutches and just hardly can walk on crutches.
So a couple of our four workers there help him get up the steps and get him onto the stuff, get up the steps and onto the stage.
And he wobbles out across the stage and just barely could get to the president.
Just stuck his hand out very limber, very slowly.

as though he were about to pass out at that moment, and the president handed him his diploma, shook his hand, and he threw down the crutches and jumped up and let out a whoop and took off running across the stage and left the crutches on the stage.
That one I remember very well.
All right, now the diploma presentation I remember most is the last one while I was employed here.
The last commencement I attended was on Saturday morning in May of 1980.
And this was a young woman getting a degree in biomedical sciences.
And do you remember who I'm thinking about?
I think you're talking, she was in the cadet corps.
That's right.
Describe, if you will, your recollection of what happened.
All right, we're talking about Melanie Zingrass.
That's right.
Melanie Zingroup was a cadet.
And when she walked up on the stage, Dr. Miller was president at that time.
And of course, her name was called.
Our commencement speaker had been Lieutenant Governor William P. Hobby.
That I did not recall.
Yes.
All right.
I think maybe that we need to possibly indicate that there were difficulties between Ms. Ingraf and the administration.
Yes.
And I recall it had to do with the
